narratives.question_text:
What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
(Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: I learned about the science behind many of the modern technologies that rule today's society.
I learned the underlying science of many modern technologies, the course was a wide survey of concepts such as electromagnetism, digital encoding and virtual optic displays.
The physics behind technological advancements and the role physics plays in everyday life
basic understanding of physics principles that underlie modern tech
Basic understanding of the science behind modern technologies.
Ability to explain the physical principles behind a lot of things in daily lives.
I learned how stuff works. I gained a basic understanding of a myriad of technical concepts and the real-world application thereof, which was very exciting and motivating.
Develop a TON of foundational knowledge of how technological systems work, particularly with a focus on EM waves/light and electromagnetism.
basics physics concepts from magnetism to waves. gained key insights into how motors, generators, solar panels, hard drives etc. worked from a physics perspective.
I gained an understanding of many technologies that I hadn't thought deeply about before
This class provided the basic language and concepts to understand most of contemporary technology.
Introductory physics and its basic applications
Gained a better understanding of the underlying mechanisms of many everyday objects.
A good foundation of basic physics used to understand technologies.
Physics

This was a great intro class to a variety of physics topics. We learned a new concept in physics and it was followed by understanding a variety of applications. About half the content was similar to AP Physics in high school.
Science concepts especially in magnetism, electricity, photons, and ways in which common technologies apply such concepts

A lot of really practically useful fundamental physics/tech concepts which can be used to understand other ones we want to learn about in the future. Also information about how individual everyday technologies work.
I learned a lot about modern technologies and basic physics! I have a much better understanding of how a lot of things work now.
Applied physics and basic mathematics

I have taken AP Physics C before, so lots of the physics knowledge in this course is a repetition for me. But Still, I love how the professor discusses the technological applications of these knowledge, and particularly like the additional lectures on bitcoin at the end.
Learned real world applications of physics concepts.

I learned the basics of physics including the nature of electrons, sound waves, light waves, magnets, electricity, and more. We learned the mechanics behind different technologies we interact with on a daily basis including microwaves, phones, speakers, cameras, etc.
Physics and math
Learned how everyday technology is broken down to equations, numbers, and other physics components
I learned a ton of physics, and how the physical aspect of technology works. I'm a CS major and the entire class was still new to me.
I learned how commonly used technologies in the world work, which we often take for granted.

I learned how many aspects of modern technological innovations work on a level understandable for non-STEM students. The course explains scientific strategies through a lens on modern products, making the physics and mechanics content easily comprehensible.
I learned basic concepts in physics, and more broadly, I gained a much greater appreciation for the complexity behind pieces of technology I ordinarily take for granted.

narratives.question_text:
What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
(Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: Strengths: homework is not too stressful, content is great, lecturer is very good at explaining the content, and the pace  and flow of the course from subject to subject made the class even better.

This is definitely the course for anyone interested in physics or the underlying science of modern technology but has little to no previous experience. If one already has taken introductory physics much of the course will probably be a review. Additionally, the PSETs at times had problems which were difficult to answer using just the information given in lecture.
I liked the real world applications mentioned in the course.

strengths: lots of office hours
weaknesses: lectures could be confusing at times and lecture slides weren't always posted
The course is overall very good, but the degree of difficulty of the problem sets is bigger than that of the lectures. This made me a little out of place in the beginning.

For me the course was at its strongest when it was explaining how a piece of technology that I've used actually works, even on a slightly basic level. Making sure each concept directly correlates to something students have experienced is really important and what makes the class so interesting.

Strengths - clear instruction, interesting material
Weaknesses - can't think of any

Strengths: 
- Right balance of physics and application to technologies
- Poll everywhere questions incentivized attendance to live lectures
- Professors and TAs were very responsive to questions/understanding about the challenges of a virtual semester
- Had worthwhile science content for non-STEM major (i.e. not a complete science gut, but also not overly difficult for non-STEM folks)

Weaknesses:
- Too many problem sets (had 12 psets; can cut down to 10 psets). Not super time consuming or difficult, but honestly some psets weren't really necessary
- Unclear grading curve. Students should be provided a more concrete idea of the grading curve in the syllabus (i.e. what percent of the class gets a particular grade on an average year?) or at least a midpoint check-in of "if you are above X % in this class at the moment, you are currently sitting at a grade of X." It's the end of the semester, and I don't have a good idea of where I stand in the class besides above the median

lectures are well organized and prof miller is good at explaining concepts, very helpful for people who know nothing about physics. office hours were also helpful and the final project was very flexible and accommodated a range of interests.
This class made seemingly challenging concepts very clear. The main weakness was the lack of in-person/live engagement with Prof. Miller, the TAs, or other students.
the midterm was very difficult in comparison to the lectures and problem sets
The course material was very interesting, especially seeing the applications of technology we see and use everyday. That is a definite strength.
Nice lectures and a lot of material covered.
Good teacher

Strenghts: For participation, the professor asked us two questions per class on Poll Everywhere. These were a great way for students to test if we were understanding the topics learned that class or if we had to go back to review/go to office hours. Additionally, it was really interesting to learn about the applications of the concepts that were taught. We learned how parts of our phones work, how Wifi, turbines, glasses, rainbows, etc.

having virtual zoom lectures with low interactivity made it hard to focus during class. this was true of many classes this year, I found that the ones which sent us to breakout rooms or which encouraged more active participation were the ones I enjoyed most and felt like I learned the most from. so not a unique problem but nonetheless a difficulty which I associated with this course.

Strengths: Class is entertaining and lots of examples and demonstrations.

Weaknesses: PSET questions have math and formulas not covered in class.

Strength: Owen Miller is a really great professor. I wish I wouldve been able to interact with him in person.

Weakness: pset material and actual lecture content are different
Interesting lectures. Didnt like the late work policy.

strengths: truly very enlightening, practical knowledge, fun final project, wide breadth of topics covered
weaknesses: at times, though our lectures were fascinating, the math that showed up on our Psets was not covered in lectures and left a lot of us hanging. Would be impossible without office hours
Good visual aides

TF office hours were structured so well, they helped me complete problem sets
Participation was calculated in a fair wayeven students who could not attend synchronously had the chance to earn participation points
Could improve on the break down of the physics part of lecture (dedicating more time to the details)

Prof Miller is engaging and friendly, and he explains concepts very clearly. I liked the demonstrations. I wish other students used Ed more because some pset questions were confusing and others definitely asked clarification questions just not on Ed.

Professor Miller was great and knows the material well, which is challenging since the breadth of material is so vast. The problem sets were all very doable and fun, and I really enjoyed the course content.

First of all, the professor was incredible. He encourages questions, maintains good communication with the class, and clearly cares about the course and his students. A major strength of the course is that it makes difficult technology accessible to understand for non-STEM students by redirecting us from difficult texts in favor of professor and student-created guides. The problem sets were not insane, but attending office hours often felt mandatory. Online sources of help stick to scientific terminology, so this class is somewhat self-contained. On the (rare) occassion where the professor forgot to mention something in a lecture, figuring out problem sets in-between office hours felt frustrating. The biggest strength of the course is the way it encourages students to learn more within problem sets. I remember feeling amazed when a problem revealed at the end how a microphone works. Overall stellar class.

Lectures were always really interesting, and I felt that the course was very well taught. Prof. Miller is fantastic and very accessible. The material was complex but well-explained. The class is geared towards students without a strong background in science, but it's not a gut  I learned a lot every week. The only weakness I can think of is that the pace of the course, especially in the first half of the semester, was quite intense and often difficult to keep up with. I would not have been able to complete most of the early problem sets without going to office hours and truly walking through the steps of each problem. The amount of information per class at first was a bit overwhelming. This got better over the course of the semester, and Prof. Miller was very responsive to feedback.

narratives.question_text: Among the practices in this course geared toward learning during the COVID-19 pandemic, which succeeded and which could be improved? Please comment on course practices that allowed for virtual engagement. (Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: This course was well geared towards the pandemic
Virtual office hours were helpful. Poll Everywhere also forced me to go to lecture in real time

success: prerecorded lectures
need for improvement: access to class materials (like lecture slides and notes)
The course is very successful. If it's an in-person class, some applications of the physical principles can be explained more clearly.
Live zoom lecture worked well. Distributing materials to those on campus was very thoughtful and nice, and helped me be more engaged
answering questions real time seems like a really useful function on zoom. if there's a way to preserve that in person that'd be great.
The asynchronous attendance option was great as sometimes I couldn't make it to the live lectures.
Buce

Strengths: The poll everywhere questions were a great way to keep students engaged. Also, the professor had many live demonstrations which was helpful
Weaknesses: No significant weakness.
Could do with a better system than poll everywhere for participation management
There were fewer exams, which while it was nice, meant that there were fewer opportunities to improve or to do well in spite of performance on any one assignment.
Zoom
Covid practices worked for me.

I like that the lectures were live but also recorded and put on Canvas for those who couldn't make it synchronously. The make-your-own Poll Everywhere question for asynchronous students was a good way to substitute for the live Poll Everywhere's.
All of them succeed

Recorded lectures were easily accessible
Fair way to earn participation points, even when attending class asynchronously 
Great way to ask questions anonymously
I really liked the Poll Everywhere questions

Having poll everywhere questions during lecture actually made me go to lecture live rather than recorded. This generally helps students learn better (including myself), however it is admittedly hard to get students engaged a lot of the time. Having the poll questions kept me engaged.

Lecture and slideshows worked pretty great. Increased digital clarification made managing schedules and overall class-related questions more manageable. Biggest issue was the inability to get access to 3D glasses and polarizers for class, as well as blurry in-class demonstrations. Also problem with in-class Q&A. The class clearly encourages student engagement in lectures, but digital setting made that difficult.
Prof. Miller made great use of multimedia technology and the asynchronous lecture option was really helpful when, inevitably, technological issues and other conflicts came up.

narratives.question_text:
Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
(Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: Absolutely. Owen Miller is a great lecturer and explains the already interest content in a way that is enjoyable.
This is definitely the course for anyone interested in physics or the underlying science of modern technology but has little to no previous experience
Yes if you are interested in technology
sure, its a great class to knock out your science requirement
Highly recommend
Yes, if you are interested in physics and the science behind things.

This is a great science credit, but not a complete gut. Absolutely take it if you're at all interesting in how the technology you have used works. If learning how a motor, generator, guitar, microphone, and spotlight works sounds like a good time, this is absolutely the class for you. Study for the midterm though!

Absolutely!! Very, very interesting course with a very good instructor (Professor Miller). If you're interested in how the tech we use in our everyday lives works, you won't regret taking this class at all. Really enjoyed the class and the professor.

Yes! Professor Miller is a good instructor who has reasonable expectations for his students. It's pretty clear that he knows that this class is aimed for students who are just trying to fulfill the science distributional requirement, but he still tries to give students an understanding of key technologies--to a conversational degree at least. That being said, there are probably easier classes for non-STEM students to fulfill their science requirement. This one will require you to do some work, especially on the quantitative side. I had some STEM background from high school and am in QR-heavy majors, which definitely helped. 

TLDR: If you took high school physics (especially APs) and were half decent at it, this shouldn't be too difficult of a class for you. If you are numbers-adverse, take a different science class (bio the world and us or something along those lines).
Yes if you want to gain a deeper understanding of many technologies
yes, if they're looking for a sc course that's not too challenging and has some real world applications. studying for the midterm took some time but the weekly psets are not very challenging.

For sure! A great and very interesting course overall. Took it as a gutty science class for senior spring and it lived up to my expectations. Was super interesting in terms of content, and midterm and final video project were easy enough. Other than that it's just weekly psets.
Yes, although the class is not a gut, its really useful for any student not in STEM to improve your scientific literacy.
I would recommend this course to another student, regardless of technological background. The course was very interesting, ad the problem sets were very manageable
This course was great in how it demonstrated everyday applications of the scientific concepts we learned, would recommend to anyone.

I would recommend it to non stem majors who like physics or are just interested in understanding how some technologies work. However I would not recommend it to someone looking for a gut because this is not a gut  you actually have to learn a decent amount of physics, but its interesting in the end!
Good for liberal arts

Yes! This is a great physics class and science credit for all students, both STEM and non-STEM. The professor does a great job introducing the concepts with live examples which helps understand what is being taught. There are also many practice questions provided to prepare for the exam.
Great fun little course especially to learn about the cool ways everyday technologies around us use basic science concepts!

Yeah, I think this is a decent science credit for anyone who isn't a STEM major - as someone who falls into that category, I found the material to be approachable and that it was rewarding to work on the trickier concepts and then understand them. Not a gut, but also not one that I regret taking or went credit/d/fail. It was cool to be able to explain a lot of these everyday technologies to my family at dinner, definitely you leave with some tangible knowledge which will make you look smart out in the world (lol)
Yes, it is a great class for non-science majors. It was entertaining and not too hard!
Sure, but this is not a complete gut. Def on the easier side but there is a decent time commitment
Yes, the technological applications of simple physics are taught excellently!
If the student is not a science major.

Yes! I genuinely learned a lot about how things around me work and will not forget the stuff I learned, because it is so practical. If you are a humanities major, I definitely recommend this class for your SC or QR as it doesn't assume a ton of prior knowledge, so the playing field feels equal. If you put in effort and go to office hours, you should be fine in this class.
Yes, I would, because Prof. Miller and the teaching fellows were fantastic.
Yes because you learn a lot about technology
This course is meant for students who do enjoy learning applied physics. However, if you struggle with physics problems then it will be very difficult to complete this independently.

Yeah, I'm a CS major so I was worried some would be repetitive, but it was basically all new to me. I have a newfound appreciation for the physical aspects/reality of technology and now actually know things my parents can be impressed by haha. Prof Miller is really friendly, and the workload is pretty light it just sucks having a pset every week.

Yes, I would recommend this course. It's probably the easiest course I've taken at Yale (and I just graduated). 100% take it for your science credit. If you took AP Physics at all in high school, the first third of the class will be extremely easy for you (it all should be easy, but there is a ton of overlap especially the electricity and magnetism material). Problem sets were super easy and doable, and lecture + the material were generally fun.

I would recommend this course to students without a deep background in science who are looking for an accessible but challenging course! Class was always interesting and I am so glad I took this instead of a gut science where I would not have learned nearly as much.
